# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: differential-topology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] In mathematics, **cobordism** is a fundamental equivalence relation on the class of compact manifolds of the same dimension, set up using the concept of the boundary (French *bord*, giving *cobordism*) of a manifold.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Two manifolds of the same dimension are *cobordant* if their disjoint union is the *boundary* of a compact manifold one dimension higher.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The boundary of a compact $(n+1)$ -dimensional manifold W is an n -dimensional manifold $\partial W$ that is closed, i.e., with empty boundary.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] In general, a closed manifold need not be a boundary: cobordism theory is the study of the difference between all closed manifolds and those that are boundaries.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The theory was originally developed by René Thom for smooth manifolds (i.e., differentiable), but there are now also versions for piecewise linear and topological manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] A *cobordism* between manifolds M and N is a compact manifold W whose boundary is the disjoint union of M and N , $\partial W=M\sqcup N$ .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Cobordisms are studied both for the equivalence relation that they generate, and as objects in their own right.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Cobordism is a much coarser equivalence relation than diffeomorphism or homeomorphism of manifolds, and is significantly easier to study and compute.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] It is not possible to classify manifolds up to diffeomorphism or homeomorphism in dimensions ≥ 4 – because the word problem for groups cannot be solved – but it is possible to classify manifolds up to cobordism.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Cobordisms are central objects of study in geometric topology and algebraic topology.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] In geometric topology, cobordisms are intimately connected with Morse theory, and *h*-cobordisms are fundamental in the study of high-dimensional manifolds, namely surgery theory.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] In algebraic topology, cobordism theories are fundamental extraordinary cohomology theories, and categories of cobordisms are the domains of topological quantum field theories.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Roughly speaking, an n -dimensional manifold M is a topological space locally (i.e., near each point) homeomorphic to an open subset of Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Those points without a neighborhood homeomorphic to an open subset of Euclidean space are the boundary points of M ; the boundary of M is denoted by $\partial M$ .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Finally, a closed manifold is, by definition, a compact manifold without boundary ( $\partial M=\emptyset$ ).
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The terminology is usually abbreviated to $(W;M,N)$ .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] M and N are called *cobordant* if such a cobordism exists.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] All manifolds cobordant to a fixed given manifold M form the *cobordism class* of M .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Every closed manifold M is the boundary of the non-compact manifold $M\times [0,1)$ ; for this reason we require W to be compact in the definition of cobordism.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Note however that W is *not* required to be connected; as a consequence, if $M=\partial W_{1}$ and $N=\partial W_{2}$ , then M and N are cobordant.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The simplest example of a cobordism is the unit interval $I=[0,1]$ .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] It is a 1-dimensional cobordism between the 0-dimensional manifolds $\{0\}$ , $\{1\}$ .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] More generally, for any closed manifold M , $(M\times I;M\times \{0\},M\times \{1\})$ is a cobordism from $M\times \{0\}$ to $M\times \{1\}$ .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] If M consists of a circle, and N of two circles, M and N together make up the boundary of a pair of pants W (see the figure at right).
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Thus the pair of pants is a cobordism between M and N .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] A simpler cobordism between M and N is given by the disjoint union of three disks.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] An *n*-manifold *M* is called *null-cobordant* if there is a cobordism between *M* and the empty manifold; in other words, if *M* is the entire boundary of some (*n* + 1)-manifold.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] For example, the circle is null-cobordant since it bounds a disk.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] More generally, a *n*-sphere is null-cobordant since it bounds a (*n* + 1)-disk.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Also, every orientable surface is null-cobordant, because it is the boundary of a handlebody.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] On the other hand, the 2*n*-dimensional real projective space $\mathbb {P} ^{2n}(\mathbb {R} )$ is a (compact) closed manifold that is not the boundary of a manifold, as is explained below.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The general *bordism problem* is to calculate the cobordism classes of manifolds subject to various conditions.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Null-cobordisms with additional structure are called fillings.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] *Bordism* and *cobordism* are used by some authors interchangeably; others distinguish them.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] When one wishes to distinguish the study of cobordism classes from the study of cobordisms as objects in their own right, one calls the equivalence question *bordism of manifolds*, and the study of cobordisms as objects *cobordisms of manifolds*.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The term *bordism* comes from French *bord*, meaning boundary.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Hence bordism is the study of boundaries.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] *Cobordism* means "jointly bound", so *M* and *N* are cobordant if they jointly bound a manifold; i.e., if their disjoint union is a boundary.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Further, cobordism groups form an extraordinary *cohomology theory*, hence the co-.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The above is the most basic form of the definition.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] It is also referred to as unoriented bordism.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] In many situations, the manifolds in question are oriented, or carry some other additional structure referred to as G-structure.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] This gives rise to "oriented cobordism" and "cobordism with G-structure", respectively.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Under favourable technical conditions these form a graded ring called the **cobordism ring** $\Omega _{*}^{G}$ , with grading by dimension, addition by disjoint union and multiplication by cartesian product.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The cobordism groups $\Omega _{*}^{G}$ are the coefficient groups of a generalised homology theory.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] When there is additional structure, the notion of cobordism must be formulated more precisely: a *G*-structure on *W* restricts to a *G*-structure on *M* and *N*.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The basic examples are *G* = O for unoriented cobordism, *G* = SO for oriented cobordism, and *G* = U for complex cobordism using *stably* complex manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] In a similar vein, a standard tool in surgery theory is surgery on normal maps: such a process changes a normal map to another normal map within the same bordism class.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Instead of considering additional structure, it is also possible to take into account various notions of manifold, especially piecewise linear (PL) and topological manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] This gives rise to bordism groups $\Omega _{*}^{PL}(X),\Omega _{*}^{TOP}(X)$ , which are harder to compute than the differentiable variants.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Recall that in general, if *X*, *Y* are manifolds with boundary, then the boundary of the product manifold is ∂(*X* × *Y*) = (∂*X* × *Y*) ∪ (*X* × ∂*Y*).
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Note that *M* is obtained from *N* by surgery on $\mathbb {D} ^{p+1}\times \mathbb {S} ^{q-1}\subset N.$ This is called **reversing the surgery**.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Every cobordism is a union of elementary cobordisms, by the work of Marston Morse, René Thom and John Milnor.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] As per the above definition, a surgery on the circle consists of cutting out a copy of $\mathbb {S} ^{0}\times \mathbb {D} ^{1}$ and gluing in $\mathbb {D} ^{1}\times \mathbb {S} ^{0}.$ The pictures in Fig.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] 2b), the resulting manifold is the torus $\mathbb {S} ^{1}\times \mathbb {S} ^{1}$ but if they are different, we obtain the Klein bottle (Fig.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Suppose that *f* is a Morse function on an (*n* + 1)-dimensional manifold, and suppose that *c* is a critical value with exactly one critical point in its preimage.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] If the index of this critical point is *p* + 1, then the level-set *N* := *f*−1(*c* + ε) is obtained from *M* := *f*−1(*c* − ε) by a *p*-surgery.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The inverse image *W* := *f*−1([*c* − ε, *c* + ε]) defines a cobordism (*W*; *M*, *N*) that can be identified with the trace of this surgery.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] By general position, one can assume *f* is Morse and such that all critical points occur in the interior of *W*.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] In this setting *f* is called a Morse function on a cobordism.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The cobordism (*W*; *M*, *N*) is a union of the traces of a sequence of surgeries on *M*, one for each critical point of *f*.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The manifold *W* is obtained from *M* × [0, 1] by attaching one handle for each critical point of *f*.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The Morse/Smale theorem states that for a Morse function on a cobordism, the flowlines of *f′* give rise to a handle presentation of the triple (*W*; *M*, *N*).
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Conversely, given a handle decomposition of a cobordism, it comes from a suitable Morse function.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] In a suitably normalized setting this process gives a correspondence between handle decompositions and Morse functions on a cobordism.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Cobordism had its roots in the (failed) attempt by Henri Poincaré in 1895 to define homology purely in terms of manifolds (Dieudonné 1989, p.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Poincaré simultaneously defined both homology and cobordism, which are not the same, in general.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] See Cobordism as an extraordinary cohomology theory for the relationship between bordism and homology.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Bordism was explicitly introduced by Lev Pontryagin in geometric work on manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] It came to prominence when René Thom showed that cobordism groups could be computed by means of homotopy theory, via the Thom complex construction.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Cobordism theory became part of the apparatus of extraordinary cohomology theory, alongside K-theory.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] It performed an important role, historically speaking, in developments in topology in the 1950s and early 1960s, in particular in the Hirzebruch–Riemann–Roch theorem, and in the first proofs of the Atiyah–Singer index theorem.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] In the 1980s the category with compact manifolds as objects and cobordisms between these as morphisms played a basic role in the Atiyah–Segal axioms for topological quantum field theory, which is an important part of quantum topology.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Cobordisms are objects of study in their own right, apart from cobordism classes.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Cobordisms form a category whose objects are closed manifolds and whose morphisms are cobordisms.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Roughly speaking, composition is given by gluing together cobordisms end-to-end: the composition of (*W*; *M*, *N*) and (*W* ′; *N*, *P*) is defined by gluing the right end of the first to the left end of the second, yielding (*W* ′ ∪*N* *W*; *M*, *P*).
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] A cobordism is a kind of cospan: *M* → *W* ← *N*.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The category is a dagger compact category.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] A topological quantum field theory is a monoidal functor from a category of cobordisms to a category of vector spaces.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] That is, it is a functor whose value on a disjoint union of manifolds is equivalent to the tensor product of its values on each of the constituent manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] In low dimensions, the bordism question is relatively trivial, but the category of cobordism is not.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] For instance, the disk bounding the circle corresponds to a nullary (0-ary) operation, while the cylinder corresponds to a 1-ary operation and the pair of pants to a binary operation.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The set of cobordism classes of closed unoriented *n*-dimensional manifolds is usually denoted by ${\mathfrak {N}}_{n}$ (rather than the more systematic $\Omega _{n}^{\text{O}}$ ); it is an abelian group with the disjoint union as operation.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] More specifically, if [*M*] and [*N*] denote the cobordism classes of the manifolds *M* and *N* respectively, we define $[M]+[N]=[M\sqcup N]$ ; this is a well-defined operation which turns ${\mathfrak {N}}_{n}$ into an abelian group.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The identity element of this group is the class $[\emptyset ]$ consisting of all closed *n*-manifolds which are boundaries.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Further we have $[M]+[M]=[\emptyset ]$ for every *M* since $M\sqcup M=\partial (M\times [0,1])$ .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Therefore, ${\mathfrak {N}}_{n}$ is a vector space over $\mathbb {F} _{2}$ , the field with two elements.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] is a graded algebra, with the grading given by the dimension.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The cobordism class $[M]\in {\mathfrak {N}}_{n}$ of a closed unoriented *n*-dimensional manifold *M* is determined by the Stiefel–Whitney characteristic numbers of *M*, which depend on the stable isomorphism class of the tangent bundle.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Thus if *M* has a stably trivial tangent bundle then $[M]=0\in {\mathfrak {N}}_{n}$ .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] the polynomial algebra with one generator $x_{i}$ in each dimension $i\neq 2^{j}-1$ .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] For even *i* it is possible to choose $x_{i}=\left[\mathbb {P} ^{i}(\mathbb {R} )\right]$ , the cobordism class of the *i*-dimensional real projective space.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] This shows, for example, that every 3-dimensional closed manifold is the boundary of a 4-manifold (with boundary).
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The Euler characteristic $\chi (M)\in \mathbb {Z}$ modulo 2 of an unoriented manifold *M* is an unoriented cobordism invariant.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] for any compact manifold with boundary W .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Therefore, $\chi :{\mathfrak {N}}_{i}\to \mathbb {Z} /2$ is a well-defined group homomorphism.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] In particular such a product of real projective spaces is not null-cobordant.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Cobordism can also be defined for manifolds that have additional structure, notably an orientation.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] This is made formal in a general way using the notion of *X*-structure (or G-structure).
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Given a collection of spaces and maps *Xk* → *Xk*+1 with maps *Xk* → *BO*(*k*) (compatible with the inclusions *BO*(*k*) → *BO*(*k*+1), an *X*-structure is a lift of ν to a map ${\tilde {\nu }}:M\to X_{k}$ .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Considering only manifolds and cobordisms with *X*-structure gives rise to a more general notion of cobordism.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] In particular, *Xk* may be given by *BG*(*k*), where *G*(*k*) → *O*(*k*) is some group homomorphism.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Examples include *G* = *O*, the orthogonal group, giving back the unoriented cobordism, but also the subgroup SO(*k*), giving rise to oriented cobordism, the spin group, the unitary group *U*(*k*), and the trivial group, giving rise to framed cobordism.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The resulting cobordism groups are then defined analogously to the unoriented case.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Oriented cobordism is the one of manifolds with an SO-structure.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Equivalently, all manifolds need to be oriented and cobordisms (*W*, *M*, *N*) (also referred to as *oriented cobordisms* for clarity) are such that the boundary (with the induced orientations) is $M\sqcup (-N)$ , where −*N* denotes *N* with the reversed orientation.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] For example, boundary of the cylinder *M* × *I* is $M\sqcup (-M)$ : both ends have opposite orientations.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] It is also the correct definition in the sense of extraordinary cohomology theory.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] of the complex projective spaces (Thom, 1952).
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The oriented cobordism group $\Omega _{*}^{\text{SO}}$ is determined by the Stiefel–Whitney and Pontrjagin characteristic numbers (Wall, 1960).
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Two oriented manifolds are oriented cobordant if and only if their Stiefel–Whitney and Pontrjagin numbers are the same.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The signature map $\sigma :\Omega _{4i}^{\text{SO}}\to \mathbb {Z}$ is onto for all *i* ≥ 1, and an isomorphism for *i* = 1.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Every vector bundle theory (real, complex etc.) has an extraordinary cohomology theory called K-theory.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Similarly, every cobordism theory Ω*G* has an extraordinary cohomology theory, with homology ("bordism") groups $\Omega _{n}^{G}(X)$ and cohomology ("cobordism") groups $\Omega _{G}^{n}(X)$ for any space *X*.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The generalized homology groups $\Omega _{*}^{G}(X)$ are covariant in *X*, and the generalized cohomology groups $\Omega _{G}^{*}(X)$ are contravariant in *X*.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The cobordism groups defined above are, from this point of view, the homology groups of a point: $\Omega _{n}^{G}=\Omega _{n}^{G}({\text{pt}})$ .
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Then $\Omega _{n}^{G}(X)$ is the group of *bordism* classes of pairs (*M*, *f*) with *M* a closed *n*-dimensional manifold *M* (with G-structure) and *f* : *M* → *X* a map.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Such pairs (*M*, *f*), (*N*, *g*) are *bordant* if there exists a G-cobordism (*W*; *M*, *N*) with a map *h* : *W* → *X*, which restricts to *f* on *M*, and to *g* on *N*.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] which is far from being an isomorphism in general.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The bordism and cobordism theories of a space satisfy the Eilenberg–Steenrod axioms apart from the dimension axiom.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] This does not mean that the groups $\Omega _{G}^{n}(X)$ can be effectively computed once one knows the cobordism theory of a point and the homology of the space *X*, though the Atiyah–Hirzebruch spectral sequence gives a starting point for calculations.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Other cobordism theories do not reduce to ordinary homology in this way, notably framed cobordism, oriented cobordism and complex cobordism.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] The last-named theory in particular is much used by algebraic topologists as a computational tool (e.g., for the homotopy groups of spheres).
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Cobordism theories are represented by Thom spectra *MG*: given a group *G*, the Thom spectrum is composed from the Thom spaces *MGn* of the standard vector bundles over the classifying spaces *BGn*.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Note that even for similar groups, Thom spectra can be very different: *MSO* and *MO* are very different, reflecting the difference between oriented and unoriented cobordism.
[src:differential-topology/cobordism] Wall proved that two manifolds are cobordant if and only if their Pontrjagin numbers and Stiefel numbers are the same.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] It is a cohomology theory based on the existence of differential forms with prescribed properties.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] On any smooth manifold, every exact form is closed, but the converse may fail to hold.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Roughly speaking, this failure is related to the possible existence of "holes" in the manifold, and the **de Rham cohomology groups** comprise a set of topological invariants of smooth manifolds that precisely quantify this relationship.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] where $\Omega ^{0}(M)$ is the space of smooth functions on M , $\Omega ^{1}(M)$ is the space of 1-forms, and so forth.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] In contrast, closed forms are not necessarily exact.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] An illustrative case is a circle as a manifold, and the 1 -form corresponding to the derivative of angle from a reference point at its centre, typically written as ${\text{d}}\theta$ (described at *Closed and exact differential forms*).
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] There is no function $\theta$ defined on the whole circle such that ${\text{d}}\theta$ is its derivative; the increase of $2\pi$ in going once around the circle in the positive direction implies a multivalued function $\theta$ .
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Removing one point of the circle obviates this, at the same time changing the topology of the manifold.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] One prominent example when all closed forms are exact is when the underlying space is contractible to a point or, more generally, if it is simply connected (no-holes condition).
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] In this case the exterior derivative d restricted to closed forms has a local inverse called a homotopy operator.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Since it is also nilpotent, it forms a dual chain complex with the arrows reversed compared to the de Rham complex.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] This is the situation described in the Poincaré lemma.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] The idea behind de Rham cohomology is to define equivalence classes of closed forms on a manifold.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] One classifies two closed forms $\alpha ,\beta \in \Omega ^{k}(M)$ as **cohomologous** if they differ by an exact form, that is, if $\alpha -\beta$ is exact.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] This classification induces an equivalence relation on the space of closed forms in $\Omega ^{k}(M)$ .
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] One then defines the k -th **de Rham cohomology group** $H_{\mathrm {dR} }^{k}(M)$ to be the set of equivalence classes, that is, the set of closed forms in $\Omega ^{k}(M)$ modulo the exact forms.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] This follows from the fact that any smooth function on M with zero derivative everywhere is separately constant on each of the connected components of M .
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] One may often find the general de Rham cohomologies of a manifold using the above fact about the zero cohomology and a Mayer–Vietoris sequence.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Another useful fact is that the de Rham cohomology is a homotopy invariant.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] For the n-sphere, $S^{n}$ , and also when taken together with a product of open intervals, we have the following.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Let $n>0$ , $m\geq 0$ , and I be an open real interval.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] The n -torus is the Cartesian product: $T^{n}=\underbrace {S^{1}\times \cdots \times S^{1}} _{n}$ .
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] We can also find explicit generators for the de Rham cohomology of the torus directly using differential forms.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Given a quotient manifold $\pi :X\to X/G$ and a differential form $\omega \in \Omega ^{k}(X)$ we can say that $\omega$ is G **-invariant** if given any diffeomorphism induced by G , $\cdot g:X\to X$ we have $(\cdot g)^{*}(\omega )=\omega$ .
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] In particular, the pullback of any form on $X/G$ is G -invariant.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Also, the pullback is an injective morphism.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] But, notice that $x_{i}+\alpha$ for $\alpha \in \mathbb {R}$ is not an invariant 0 -form.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Since the cohomology ring of a torus is generated by $H^{1}$ , taking the exterior products of these forms gives all of the explicit representatives for the de Rham cohomology of a torus.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Punctured Euclidean space is simply $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ with the origin removed.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Stokes' theorem is an expression of duality between de Rham cohomology and the homology of chains.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] The theorem of de Rham asserts that this is an isomorphism between de Rham cohomology and singular cohomology.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] The exterior product endows the direct sum of these groups with a ring structure.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] A further result of the theorem is that the two cohomology rings are isomorphic (as graded rings), where the analogous product on singular cohomology is the cup product.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] For any smooth manifold M , let ${\textstyle {\underline {\mathbb {R} }}}$ be the constant sheaf on M associated to the abelian group ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} }$ ; in other words, ${\textstyle {\underline {\mathbb {R} }}}$ is the sheaf of locally constant real-valued functions on M .
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] between the de Rham cohomology and the sheaf cohomology of ${\textstyle {\underline {\mathbb {R} }}}$ .
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] The standard proof proceeds by showing that the de Rham complex, when viewed as a complex of sheaves, is an acyclic resolution of ${\textstyle {\underline {\mathbb {R} }}}$ .
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] In more detail, let m be the dimension of M and let ${\textstyle \Omega ^{k}}$ denote the sheaf of germs of k -forms on M (with ${\textstyle \Omega ^{0}}$ the sheaf of ${\textstyle C^{\infty }}$ functions on M ).
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] where by exactness we have isomorphisms ${\textstyle \operatorname {im} d_{k-1}\cong \ker d_{k}}$ for all k .
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Each of these induces a long exact sequence in cohomology.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Since the sheaf ${\textstyle \Omega ^{0}}$ of ${\textstyle C^{\infty }}$ functions on M admits partitions of unity, any ${\textstyle \Omega ^{0}}$ -module is a fine sheaf; in particular, the sheaves ${\textstyle \Omega ^{k}}$ are all fine.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Therefore, the sheaf cohomology groups ${\textstyle H^{i}(M,\Omega ^{k})}$ vanish for ${\textstyle i>0}$ since all fine sheaves on paracompact spaces are acyclic.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] So the long exact cohomology sequences themselves ultimately separate into a chain of isomorphisms.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] At one end of the chain is the sheaf cohomology of ${\textstyle {\underline {\mathbb {R} }}}$ and at the other lies the de Rham cohomology.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] The de Rham cohomology has inspired many mathematical ideas, including Dolbeault cohomology, Hodge theory, and the Atiyah–Singer index theorem.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] However, even in more classical contexts, the theorem has inspired a number of developments.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Firstly, the Hodge theory proves that there is an isomorphism between the cohomology consisting of harmonic forms and the de Rham cohomology consisting of closed forms modulo exact forms.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] This relies on an appropriate definition of harmonic forms and of the Hodge theorem.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] If M is a compact Riemannian manifold, then each equivalence class in $H_{\mathrm {dR} }^{k}(M)$ contains exactly one harmonic form.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] where $\alpha$ is exact and $\gamma$ is harmonic: $\Delta \gamma =0$ .
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Any harmonic function on a compact connected Riemannian manifold is a constant.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Thus, this particular representative element can be understood to be an extremum (a minimum) of all cohomologously equivalent forms on the manifold.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] For example, on a 2 -torus, one may envision a constant 1 -form as one where all of the "hair" is combed neatly in the same direction (and all of the "hair" having the same length).
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] In this case, there are two cohomologically distinct combings; all of the others are linear combinations.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] In particular, this implies that the 1st Betti number of a 2 -torus is two.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] More generally, on an n -dimensional torus $T^{n}$ , one can consider the various combings of k -forms on the torus.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] There are n choose k such combings that can be used to form the basis vectors for $H_{\text{dR}}^{k}(T^{n})$ ; the k -th Betti number for the de Rham cohomology group for the n -torus is thus n choose k .
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] More precisely, for a differential manifold M , one may equip it with some auxiliary Riemannian metric.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] with d the exterior derivative and $\delta$ the codifferential.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] The Laplacian is a homogeneous (in grading) linear differential operator acting upon the exterior algebra of differential forms: we can look at its action on each component of degree k separately.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] If M is compact and oriented, the dimension of the kernel of the Laplacian acting upon the space of k-forms is then equal (by Hodge theory) to that of the de Rham cohomology group in degree k : the Laplacian picks out a unique **harmonic form** in each cohomology class of closed forms.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] In particular, the space of all harmonic k -forms on M is isomorphic to $H^{k}(M;\mathbb {R} )$ .
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] The dimension of each such space is finite, and is given by the k -th Betti number.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] Let M be a compact oriented Riemannian manifold.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] where $\alpha$ is exact, $\beta$ is co-exact, and $\gamma$ is harmonic.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] One says that a form $\beta$ is co-closed if $\delta \beta =0$ and co-exact if $\beta =\delta \eta$ for some form $\eta$ , and that $\gamma$ is harmonic if the Laplacian is zero, $\Delta \gamma =0$ .
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] This follows by noting that exact and co-exact forms are orthogonal; the orthogonal complement then consists of forms that are both closed and co-closed: that is, of harmonic forms.
[src:differential-topology/de-rham-cohomology] By use of Sobolev spaces or distributions, the decomposition can be extended for example to a complete (oriented or not) Riemannian manifold.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] In mathematics, a **differentiable manifold** (also **differential manifold**) is a type of manifold that is locally similar enough to a vector space to allow one to apply calculus.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Any manifold can be described by a collection of charts (atlas).
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] One may then apply ideas from calculus while working within the individual charts, since each chart lies within a vector space to which the usual rules of calculus apply.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] If the charts are suitably compatible (namely, the transition from one chart to another is differentiable), then computations done in one chart are valid in any other differentiable chart.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] In formal terms, a **differentiable manifold** is a topological manifold with a globally defined differential structure.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Any topological manifold can be given a differential structure locally by using the homeomorphisms in its atlas and the standard differential structure on a vector space.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] To induce a global differential structure on the local coordinate systems induced by the homeomorphisms, their compositions on chart intersections in the atlas must be differentiable functions on the corresponding vector space.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] In other words, where the domains of charts overlap, the coordinates defined by each chart are required to be differentiable with respect to the coordinates defined by every chart in the atlas.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The ability to define such a local differential structure on an abstract space allows one to extend the definition of differentiability to spaces without global coordinate systems.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A locally differential structure allows one to define the globally differentiable tangent space, differentiable functions, and differentiable tensor and vector fields.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Differentiable manifolds are very important in physics.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Special kinds of differentiable manifolds form the basis for physical theories such as classical mechanics, general relativity, and Yang–Mills theory.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] It is possible to develop a calculus for differentiable manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This leads to such mathematical machinery as the exterior calculus.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The study of calculus on differentiable manifolds is known as differential geometry.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] "Differentiability" of a manifold has been given several meanings, including: continuously differentiable, *k*-times differentiable, smooth (which itself has many meanings), and analytic.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The emergence of differential geometry as a distinct discipline is generally credited to Carl Friedrich Gauss and Bernhard Riemann.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Riemann first described manifolds in his famous habilitation lecture before the faculty at Göttingen.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Having constructed the notion of a manifoldness of n dimensions, and found that its true character consists in the property that the determination of position in it may be reduced to n determinations of magnitude, ...
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] These ideas found a key application in Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and its underlying equivalence principle.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A modern definition of a 2-dimensional manifold was given by Hermann Weyl in his 1913 book on Riemann surfaces.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The widely accepted general definition of a manifold in terms of an atlas is due to Hassler Whitney.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A **chart** (*U*, *φ*) on M consists of an open subset U of M, and a homeomorphism *φ* from U to an open subset of some Euclidean space **R***n*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Somewhat informally, one may refer to a chart *φ* : *U* → **R***n*, meaning that the image of φ is an open subset of **R***n*, and that φ is a homeomorphism onto its image; in the usage of some authors, this may instead mean that *φ* : *U* → **R***n* is itself a homeomorphism.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This situation is not fully satisfactory for the following reason.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Consider a second chart (*V*, *ψ*) on M, and suppose that U and V contain some points in common.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Since φ and *ψ* are homeomorphisms, it follows that *ψ* ∘ *φ*−1 is a homeomorphism from *φ*(*U* ∩ *V*) to *ψ*(*U* ∩ *V*).
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The same problem is found if one considers instead functions *c* : **R** → *M*; one is led to the reparametrization formula $\varphi \circ c={\big (}\varphi \circ \psi ^{-1}{\big )}\circ {\big (}\psi \circ c{\big )},$ at which point one can make the same observation as before.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This is resolved by the introduction of a "differentiable atlas" of charts, which specifies a collection of charts on M for which the transition maps *ψ* ∘ *φ*−1 are all differentiable.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This makes the situation quite clean: if *u* ∘ *φ*−1 is differentiable, then due to the first reparametrization formula listed above, the map *u* ∘ *ψ*−1 is also differentiable on the region *ψ*(*U* ∩ *V*), and vice versa.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Moreover, the derivatives of these two maps are linked to one another by the chain rule.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Relative to the given atlas, this facilitates a notion of differentiable mappings whose domain or range is M, as well as a notion of the derivative of such maps.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Formally, the word "differentiable" is somewhat ambiguous, as it is taken to mean different things by different authors; sometimes it means the existence of first derivatives, sometimes the existence of continuous first derivatives, and sometimes the existence of infinitely many derivatives.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The following gives a formal definition of various (nonambiguous) meanings of "differentiable atlas".
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Generally, "differentiable" will be used as a catch-all term including all of these possibilities, provided *k* ≥ 1.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Since every real-analytic map is smooth, and every smooth map is *C**k* for any k, one can see that any analytic atlas can also be viewed as a smooth atlas, and every smooth atlas can be viewed as a *C**k* atlas.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This chain can be extended to include holomorphic atlases, with the understanding that any holomorphic map between open subsets of **C***n* can be viewed as a real-analytic map between open subsets of **R**2*n*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A differentiable atlas determines a **maximal differentiable atlas**, consisting of all charts which are differentiably compatible with the given atlas.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] For instance, given any chart in a maximal atlas, its restriction to an arbitrary open subset of its domain will also be contained in the maximal atlas.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A maximal smooth atlas is also known as a smooth structure; a maximal holomorphic atlas is also known as a complex structure.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] An alternative but equivalent definition, avoiding the direct use of maximal atlases, is to consider equivalence classes of differentiable atlases, in which two differentiable atlases are considered equivalent if every chart of one atlas is differentiably compatible with the other atlas.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Informally, what this means is that in dealing with a smooth manifold, one can work with a single differentiable atlas, consisting of only a few charts, with the implicit understanding that many other charts and differentiable atlases are equally legitimate.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] According to the invariance of domain, each connected component of a topological space which has a differentiable atlas has a well-defined dimension n.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This causes a small ambiguity in the case of a holomorphic atlas, since the corresponding dimension will be one-half of the value of its dimension when considered as an analytic, smooth, or *C**k* atlas.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] For this reason, one refers separately to the "real" and "complex" dimension of a topological space with a holomorphic atlas.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A **differentiable manifold** is a Hausdorff and second countable topological space M, together with a maximal differentiable atlas on M.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Much of the basic theory can be developed without the need for the Hausdorff and second countability conditions, although they are vital for much of the advanced theory.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] They are essentially equivalent to the general existence of bump functions and partitions of unity, both of which are used ubiquitously.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The notion of a *C*0 manifold is identical to that of a topological manifold.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] However, there is a notable distinction to be made.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Given a topological space, it is meaningful to ask whether or not it is a topological manifold.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] By contrast, it is not meaningful to ask whether or not a given topological space is (for instance) a smooth manifold, since the notion of a smooth manifold requires the specification of a smooth atlas, which is an additional structure.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] It could, however, be meaningful to say that a certain topological space cannot be given the structure of a smooth manifold.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] It is possible to reformulate the definitions so that this sort of imbalance is not present; one can start with a set M (rather than a topological space M), using the natural analogue of a smooth atlas in this setting to define the structure of a topological space on M.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] One can reverse-engineer the above definitions to obtain one perspective on the construction of manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The idea is to start with the images of the charts and the transition maps, and to construct the manifold purely from this data.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] As in the above discussion, we use the "smooth" context but everything works just as well in other settings.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Given an indexing set $A,$ let $V_{\alpha }$ be a collection of open subsets of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and for each $\alpha ,\beta \in A$ let $V_{\alpha \beta }$ be an open (possibly empty) subset of $V_{\beta }$ and let $\phi _{\alpha \beta }:V_{\alpha \beta }\to V_{\beta \alpha }$ be a smooth map.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Suppose that $\phi _{\alpha \alpha }$ is the identity map, that $\phi _{\alpha \beta }\circ \phi _{\beta \alpha }$ is the identity map, and that $\phi _{\alpha \beta }\circ \phi _{\beta \gamma }\circ \phi _{\gamma \alpha }$ is the identity map.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] For the patching together the analytic structures(subset), see analytic varieties.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A real valued function *f* on an *n*-dimensional differentiable manifold *M* is called **differentiable** at a point *p* ∈ *M* if it is differentiable in any coordinate chart defined around *p*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] In general, there will be many available charts; however, the definition of differentiability does not depend on the choice of chart at *p*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] It follows from the chain rule applied to the transition functions between one chart and another that if *f* is differentiable in any particular chart at *p*, then it is differentiable in all charts at *p*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Analogous considerations apply to defining *Ck* functions, smooth functions, and analytic functions.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] There are various ways to define the derivative of a function on a differentiable manifold, the most fundamental of which is the directional derivative.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The definition of the directional derivative is complicated by the fact that a manifold will lack a suitable affine structure with which to define vectors.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Therefore, the directional derivative looks at curves in the manifold instead of vectors.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Given a real valued function *f* on an *n* dimensional differentiable manifold *M*, the directional derivative of *f* at a point *p* in *M* is defined as follows.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Suppose that γ(*t*) is a curve in *M* with *γ*(0) = *p*, which is *differentiable* in the sense that its composition with any chart is a differentiable curve in **R***n*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] then, by the chain rule, *f* has the same directional derivative at *p* along *γ*1 as along *γ*2.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This means that the directional derivative depends only on the tangent vector of the curve at *p*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Thus, the more abstract definition of directional differentiation adapted to the case of differentiable manifolds ultimately captures the intuitive features of directional differentiation in an affine space.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A **tangent vector** at *p* ∈ *M* is an equivalence class of differentiable curves *γ* with *γ*(0) = *p*, modulo the equivalence relation of first-order contact between the curves.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Therefore, the equivalence classes are curves through *p* with a prescribed velocity vector at *p*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The collection of all tangent vectors at *p* forms a vector space: the tangent space to *M* at *p*, denoted *T**p**M*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] If the function *f* is fixed, then the mapping $X\mapsto Xf(p)$ is a linear functional on the tangent space.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] One can check that $T_{p}M$ naturally has the structure of a n -dimensional real vector space, and that with this structure, $df_{p}$ is a linear map.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] With the idea of the formal definitions understood, this shorthand notation is, for most purposes, much easier to work with.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] One of the topological features of the sheaf of differentiable functions on a differentiable manifold is that it admits partitions of unity.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This distinguishes the differential structure on a manifold from stronger structures (such as analytic and holomorphic structures) that in general fail to have partitions of unity.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Suppose that *M* is a manifold of class *Ck*, where 0 ≤ *k* ≤ ∞.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Let {*U**α*} be an open covering of *M*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Every open covering of a *Ck* manifold *M* has a *Ck* partition of unity.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This allows for certain constructions from the topology of *Ck* functions on **R***n* to be carried over to the category of differentiable manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] In particular, it is possible to discuss integration by choosing a partition of unity subordinate to a particular coordinate atlas, and carrying out the integration in each chart of **R***n*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Partitions of unity therefore allow for certain other kinds of function spaces to be considered: for instance L*p* spaces, Sobolev spaces, and other kinds of spaces that require integration.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Suppose *M* and *N* are two differentiable manifolds with dimensions *m* and *n*, respectively, and *f* is a function from *M* to *N*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Since differentiable manifolds are topological spaces we know what it means for *f* to be continuous.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] We know what that means when *f* is a function between Euclidean spaces, so if we compose *f* with a chart of *M* and a chart of *N* such that we get a map that goes from Euclidean space to *M* to *N* to Euclidean space we know what it means for that map to be *Ck*(**R***m*, **R***n*).
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Once again, the chain rule guarantees that the idea of differentiability does not depend on which charts of the atlases on *M* and *N* are selected.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] However, defining the derivative itself is more subtle.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] If *M* or *N* is itself already a Euclidean space, then we don't need a chart to map it to one.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The tangent space of a point consists of the possible directional derivatives at that point, and has the same dimension *n* as does the manifold.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] For a set of (non-singular) coordinates *xk* local to the point, the coordinate derivatives $\partial _{k}={\frac {\partial }{\partial x_{k}}}$ define a holonomic basis of the tangent space.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The collection of tangent spaces at all points can in turn be made into a manifold, the tangent bundle, whose dimension is 2*n*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The tangent bundle is where tangent vectors lie, and is itself a differentiable manifold.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The Lagrangian is a function on the tangent bundle.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] One can also define the tangent bundle as the bundle of 1-jets from **R** (the real line) to *M*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] One may construct an atlas for the tangent bundle consisting of charts based on *U**α* × **R***n*, where *U**α* denotes one of the charts in the atlas for *M*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Each of these new charts is the tangent bundle for the charts *U**α*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The transition maps on this atlas are defined from the transition maps on the original manifold, and retain the original differentiability class.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The dual space of a vector space is the set of real valued linear functions on the vector space.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The cotangent space at a point is the dual of the tangent space at that point and the elements are referred to as cotangent vectors; the cotangent bundle is the collection of all cotangent vectors, along with the natural differentiable manifold structure.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Like the tangent bundle, the cotangent bundle is again a differentiable manifold.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The Hamiltonian is a scalar on the cotangent bundle.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The total space of a cotangent bundle has the structure of a symplectic manifold.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Cotangent vectors are sometimes called *covectors*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] One can also define the cotangent bundle as the bundle of 1-jets of functions from *M* to **R**.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Elements of the cotangent space can be thought of as infinitesimal displacements: if *f* is a differentiable function we can define at each point *p* a cotangent vector *dfp*, which sends a tangent vector *Xp* to the derivative of *f* associated with *Xp*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] However, not every covector field can be expressed this way.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Those that can are referred to as exact differentials.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] For a given set of local coordinates *xk,* the differentials *dx**k* *p* form a basis of the cotangent space at *p*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The tensor bundle is the direct sum of all tensor products of the tangent bundle and the cotangent bundle.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Each element of the bundle is a tensor field, which can act as a multilinear operator on vector fields, or on other tensor fields.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The tensor bundle is not a differentiable manifold in the traditional sense, since it is infinite dimensional.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] It is however an algebra over the ring of scalar functions.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Each tensor is characterized by its ranks, which indicate how many tangent and cotangent factors it has.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Sometimes these ranks are referred to as *covariant* and *contravariant* ranks, signifying tangent and cotangent ranks, respectively.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A frame (or, in more precise terms, a tangent frame), is an ordered basis of particular tangent space.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Likewise, a tangent frame is a linear isomorphism of **R***n* to this tangent space.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A moving tangent frame is an ordered list of vector fields that give a basis at every point of their domain.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] One may also regard a moving frame as a section of the frame bundle F(*M*), a GL(*n*, **R**) principal bundle made up of the set of all frames over *M*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The frame bundle is useful because tensor fields on *M* can be regarded as equivariant vector-valued functions on F(*M*).
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] On a manifold that is sufficiently smooth, various kinds of jet bundles can also be considered.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The (first-order) tangent bundle of a manifold is the collection of curves in the manifold modulo the equivalence relation of first-order contact.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] By analogy, the *k*-th order tangent bundle is the collection of curves modulo the relation of *k*-th order contact.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Likewise, the cotangent bundle is the bundle of 1-jets of functions on the manifold: the *k*-jet bundle is the bundle of their *k*-jets.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] These and other examples of the general idea of jet bundles play a significant role in the study of differential operators on manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The notion of a frame also generalizes to the case of higher-order jets.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Define a *k*-th order frame to be the *k*-jet of a diffeomorphism from **R***n* to *M*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The collection of all *k*-th order frames, *Fk*(*M*), is a principal *Gk* bundle over *M*, where *Gk* is the group of *k*-jets; i.e., the group made up of *k*-jets of diffeomorphisms of **R***n* that fix the origin.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Note that GL(*n*, **R**) is naturally isomorphic to *G*1, and a subgroup of every *Gk*, *k* ≥ 2.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] In particular, a section of *F*2(*M*) gives the frame components of a connection on *M*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Thus, the quotient bundle *F*2(*M*) / GL(*n*, **R**) is the bundle of *symmetric* linear connections over *M*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Many of the techniques from multivariate calculus also apply, *mutatis mutandis*, to differentiable manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] One can define the directional derivative of a differentiable function along a tangent vector to the manifold, for instance, and this leads to a means of generalizing the total derivative of a function: the differential.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] From the perspective of calculus, the derivative of a function on a manifold behaves in much the same way as the ordinary derivative of a function defined on a Euclidean space, at least locally.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] For example, there are versions of the implicit and inverse function theorems for such functions.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] There are, however, important differences in the calculus of vector fields (and tensor fields in general).
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] In brief, the directional derivative of a vector field is not well-defined, or at least not defined in a straightforward manner.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Several generalizations of the derivative of a vector field (or tensor field) do exist, and capture certain formal features of differentiation in Euclidean spaces.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Ideas from integral calculus also carry over to differential manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] These are naturally expressed in the language of exterior calculus and differential forms.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The fundamental theorems of integral calculus in several variables—namely Green's theorem, the divergence theorem, and Stokes' theorem—generalize to a theorem (also called Stokes' theorem) relating the exterior derivative and integration over submanifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Differentiable functions between two manifolds are needed in order to formulate suitable notions of submanifolds, and other related concepts.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] If *f* : *M* → *N* is a differentiable function from a differentiable manifold *M* of dimension *m* to another differentiable manifold *N* of dimension *n*, then the differential of *f* is a mapping *df* : T*M* → T*N*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] It is also denoted by *Tf* and called the **tangent map**.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] At each point of *M*, this is a linear transformation from one tangent space to another: $df(p)\colon T_{p}M\to T_{f(p)}N.$ The **rank** of *f* at *p* is the rank of this linear transformation.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Usually the rank of a function is a pointwise property.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] However, if the function has maximal rank, then the rank will remain constant in a neighborhood of a point.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A differentiable function "usually" has maximal rank, in a precise sense given by Sard's theorem.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A Lie derivative, named after Sophus Lie, is a derivation on the algebra of tensor fields over a manifold *M*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The Lie derivatives are represented by vector fields, as infinitesimal generators of flows (active diffeomorphisms) on *M*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Looking at it the other way around, the group of diffeomorphisms of *M* has the associated Lie algebra structure, of Lie derivatives, in a way directly analogous to the Lie group theory.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The exterior calculus allows for a generalization of the gradient, divergence and curl operators.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The bundle of differential forms, at each point, consists of all totally antisymmetric multilinear maps on the tangent space at that point.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] It is naturally divided into *n*-forms for each *n* at most equal to the dimension of the manifold; an *n*-form is an *n*-variable form, also called a form of degree *n*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The 1-forms are the cotangent vectors, while the 0-forms are just scalar functions.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] In general, an *n*-form is a tensor with cotangent rank *n* and tangent rank 0.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] But not every such tensor is a form, as a form must be antisymmetric.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The *exterior derivative* is a linear operator on the graded vector space of all smooth differential forms on a smooth manifold M .
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] More precisely, if $n=\dim(M)$ , for $0\leq k\leq n$ the operator d maps the space $\Omega ^{k}(M)$ of k -forms on M into the space $\Omega ^{k+1}(M)$ of $(k+1)$ -forms (if $k>n$ there are no non-zero k -forms on M so the map d is identically zero on n -forms).
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The exterior derivative also satisfies the identity $d\circ d=0$ .
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] That is, if $\omega$ is a k -form then the $(k+2)$ -form $d(df)$ is identically vanishing.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A form $\omega$ such that $d\omega =0$ is called *closed*, while a form $\omega$ such that $\omega =d\eta$ for some other form $\eta$ is called *exact*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Another formulation of the identity $d\circ d=0$ is that an exact form is closed.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This allows one to define de Rham cohomology of the manifold M , where the k th cohomology group is the quotient group of the closed forms on M by the exact forms on M .
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Suppose that M is a topological n -manifold.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Then consider the new atlas $\{(\Phi ^{-1}(U_{\alpha }),\phi _{\alpha }\circ \Phi )\}_{\alpha \in A},$ which is easily verified as a smooth atlas.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] More briefly, one could say that two smooth atlases are equivalent if there exists a diffeomorphism $M\to M,$ in which one smooth atlas is taken for the domain and the other smooth atlas is taken for the range.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Note that this equivalence relation is a refinement of the equivalence relation which defines a smooth manifold structure, as any two smoothly compatible atlases are also compatible in the present sense; one can take $\Phi$ to be the identity map.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] If the dimension of M is 1, 2, or 3, then there exists a smooth structure on M , and all distinct smooth structures are equivalent in the above sense.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The situation is more complicated in higher dimensions, although it isn't fully understood.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Every one-dimensional connected smooth manifold is diffeomorphic to either $\mathbb {R}$ or $S^{1},$ each with their standard smooth structures.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] For a classification of smooth 2-manifolds, see surface.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The situation in three dimensions is quite a bit more complicated, and known results are more indirect.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A remarkable result, proved in 2002 by methods of partial differential equations, is the geometrization conjecture, stating loosely that any compact smooth 3-manifold can be split up into different parts, each of which admits Riemannian metrics which possess many symmetries.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] There are also various "recognition results" for geometrizable 3-manifolds, such as Mostow rigidity and Sela's algorithm for the isomorphism problem for hyperbolic groups.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The classification of *n*-manifolds for *n* greater than three is known to be impossible, even up to homotopy equivalence.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Given any finitely presented group, one can construct a closed 4-manifold having that group as fundamental group.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Since there is no algorithm to decide the isomorphism problem for finitely presented groups, there is no algorithm to decide whether two 4-manifolds have the same fundamental group.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Since the previously described construction results in a class of 4-manifolds that are homeomorphic if and only if their groups are isomorphic, the homeomorphism problem for 4-manifolds is undecidable.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] In addition, since even recognizing the trivial group is undecidable, it is not even possible in general to decide whether a manifold has trivial fundamental group, i.e. is simply connected.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Simply connected 4-manifolds have been classified up to homeomorphism by Freedman using the intersection form and Kirby–Siebenmann invariant.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Smooth 4-manifold theory is known to be much more complicated, as the exotic smooth structures on **R**4 demonstrate.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] However, the situation becomes more tractable for simply connected smooth manifolds of dimension ≥ 5, where the h-cobordism theorem can be used to reduce the classification to a classification up to homotopy equivalence, and surgery theory can be applied.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This has been carried out to provide an explicit classification of simply connected 5-manifolds by Dennis Barden.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A Riemannian manifold consists of a smooth manifold together with a positive-definite inner product on each of the individual tangent spaces.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This collection of inner products is called the Riemannian metric, and is naturally a symmetric 2-tensor field.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This "metric" identifies a natural vector space isomorphism $T_{p}M\to T_{p}^{\ast }M$ for each $p\in M.$ On a Riemannian manifold one can define notions of length, volume, and angle.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Any smooth manifold can be given many different Riemannian metrics.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A pseudo-Riemannian manifold (also called a semi-Riemannian manifold) is a generalization of the notion of Riemannian manifold where the inner products are allowed to have an indefinite signature, as opposed to being positive-definite; they are still required to be non-degenerate.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Every smooth pseudo-Riemannian and Riemmannian manifold defines a number of associated tensor fields, such as the Riemann curvature tensor.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Lorentzian manifolds are pseudo-Riemannian manifolds of signature $(n-1,1)$ ; the case $n=4$ is fundamental in general relativity.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] Not every smooth manifold can be given a non-Riemannian pseudo-Riemannian structure; there are topological restrictions on doing so.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A Finsler manifold is a different generalization of a Riemannian manifold, in which the inner product is replaced with a vector norm; as such, this allows the definition of length, but not angle.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A symplectic manifold is a manifold equipped with a closed, nondegenerate 2-form.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] This condition forces symplectic manifolds to be even-dimensional, due to the fact that skew-symmetric $(2n+1)\times (2n+1)$ matrices all have zero determinant.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] A Lie group consists of a *C*∞ manifold G together with a group structure on G such that the product and inversion maps $m:G\times G\to G$ and $i:G\to G$ are smooth as maps of manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] These objects often arise naturally in describing (continuous) symmetries, and they form an important source of examples of smooth manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] In particular, by considering an arbitrary nonzero vector in $T_{e}G,$ one can use these identifications to give a smooth non-vanishing vector field on $G.$ This shows, for instance, that no even-dimensional sphere can support a Lie group structure.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p01] The same argument shows, more generally, that every Lie group must be parallelizable.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] The notion of a pseudogroup provides a flexible generalization of atlases in order to allow a variety of different structures to be defined on manifolds in a uniform way.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] If *f* is a homeomorphism from a union of open subsets of *S*, $\cup _{i}\,U_{i}$ , to an open subset of *S*, then *f* ∈ Γ provided $f|_{U_{i}}\in \Gamma$ for every *i*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] For every open *U* ⊂ *S*, the identity transformation of *U* is in Γ.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] The composition of two elements of Γ is in Γ.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] These last three conditions are analogous to the definition of a group.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Note that Γ need not be a group, however, since the functions are not globally defined on *S*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] For example, the collection of all local *Ck* diffeomorphisms on **R***n* form a pseudogroup.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] All biholomorphisms between open sets in **C***n* form a pseudogroup.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] More examples include: orientation preserving maps of **R***n*, symplectomorphisms, Möbius transformations, affine transformations, and so on.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Thus, a wide variety of function classes determine pseudogroups.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] An atlas (*Ui*, *φ**i*) of homeomorphisms *φ**i* from *Ui* ⊂ *M* to open subsets of a topological space *S* is said to be *compatible* with a pseudogroup Γ provided that the transition functions *φ**j* ∘ *φ**i*−1 : *φ**i*(*Ui* ∩ *Uj*) → *φ**j*(*Ui* ∩ *Uj*) are all in Γ.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] A differentiable manifold is then an atlas compatible with the pseudogroup of *C**k* functions on **R***n*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] A complex manifold is an atlas compatible with the biholomorphic functions on open sets in **C***n*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Thus, pseudogroups provide a single framework in which to describe many structures on manifolds of importance to differential geometry and topology.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Sometimes, it can be useful to use an alternative approach to endow a manifold with a *Ck*-structure.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Here *k* = 1, 2, ..., ∞, or ω for real analytic manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Instead of considering coordinate charts, it is possible to start with functions defined on the manifold itself.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] The structure sheaf of *M*, denoted **C***k*, is a sort of functor that defines, for each open set *U* ⊂ *M*, an algebra **C***k*(*U*) of continuous functions *U* → **R**.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] In particular, this latter condition means that any function *h* in **C***k*(*V*), for *V*, can be written uniquely as *h*(*x*) = *H*(*x*1(*x*), ..., *x**n*(*x*)), where *H* is a *k*-times differentiable function on *f*(*V*) (an open set in **R***n*).
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Thus, the sheaf-theoretic viewpoint is that the functions on a differentiable manifold can be expressed in local coordinates as differentiable functions on **R***n*, and *a fortiori* this is sufficient to characterize the differential structure on the manifold.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] A similar, but more technical, approach to defining differentiable manifolds can be formulated using the notion of a ringed space.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] This approach is strongly influenced by the theory of schemes in algebraic geometry, but uses local rings of the germs of differentiable functions.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] It is especially popular in the context of *complex* manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] We begin by describing the basic structure sheaf on **R***n*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] consist of all real-valued *k*-times continuously differentiable functions on *U*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] As *U* varies, this determines a sheaf of rings on **R**n.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] The stalk **O***p* for *p* ∈ **R***n* consists of germs of functions near *p*, and is an algebra over **R**.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] In particular, this is a local ring whose unique maximal ideal consists of those functions that vanish at *p*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] The pair (**R***n*, **O**) is an example of a locally ringed space: it is a topological space equipped with a sheaf whose stalks are each local rings.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] A differentiable manifold (of class *Ck*) consists of a pair (*M*, **O***M*) where *M* is a second countable Hausdorff space, and **O***M* is a sheaf of local **R**-algebras defined on *M*, such that the locally ringed space (*M*, **O***M*) is locally isomorphic to (**R***n*, **O**).
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] In this way, differentiable manifolds can be thought of as schemes modeled on **R***n*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] There are a number of important motivations for studying differentiable manifolds within this abstract framework.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] First, there is no *a priori* reason that the model space needs to be **R**n.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] In broader terms, this concept can be adapted for any suitable notion of a scheme (see topos theory).
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Second, coordinates are no longer explicitly necessary to the construction.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] The analog of a coordinate system is the pair (*f*, *f*#), but these merely quantify the idea of *local isomorphism* rather than being central to the discussion (as in the case of charts and atlases).
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Third, the sheaf **O***M* is not manifestly a sheaf of functions at all.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Rather, it emerges as a sheaf of functions as a *consequence* of the construction (via the quotients of local rings by their maximal ideals).
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Hence, it is a more primitive definition of the structure (see synthetic differential geometry).
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] A final advantage of this approach is that it allows for natural direct descriptions of many of the fundamental objects of study to differential geometry and topology.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] The category of smooth manifolds with smooth maps lacks certain desirable properties, and people have tried to generalize smooth manifolds in order to rectify this.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Diffeological spaces use a different notion of chart known as a "plot".
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Frölicher spaces and orbifolds are other attempts.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] A rectifiable set generalizes the idea of a piece-wise smooth or rectifiable curve to higher dimensions; however, rectifiable sets are not in general manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] Banach manifolds and Fréchet manifolds, in particular manifolds of mappings are infinite dimensional differentiable manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] For a *Ck* manifold *M*, the set of real-valued *Ck* functions on the manifold forms an algebra under pointwise addition and multiplication, called the *algebra of scalar fields* or simply the *algebra of scalars*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] This algebra has the constant function 1 as the multiplicative identity, and is a differentiable analog of the ring of regular functions in algebraic geometry.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] It is possible to reconstruct a manifold from its algebra of scalars, first as a set, but also as a topological space – this is an application of the Banach–Stone theorem, and is more formally known as the spectrum of a C*-algebra.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] First, there is a one-to-one correspondence between the points of *M* and the algebra homomorphisms *φ*: *Ck*(*M*) → **R**, as such a homomorphism *φ* corresponds to a codimension one ideal in *Ck*(*M*) (namely the kernel of *φ*), which is necessarily a maximal ideal.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] On the converse, every maximal ideal in this algebra is an ideal of functions vanishing at a single point, which demonstrates that MSpec (the Max Spec) of *Ck*(*M*) recovers *M* as a point set, though in fact it recovers *M* as a topological space.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] One can define various geometric structures algebraically in terms of the algebra of scalars, and these definitions often generalize to algebraic geometry (interpreting rings geometrically) and operator theory (interpreting Banach spaces geometrically).
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] For example, the tangent bundle to *M* can be defined as the derivations of the algebra of smooth functions on *M*.
[src:differential-topology/differentiable-manifold-p02] This is the basis of the field of noncommutative geometry.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] In mathematics, **differential topology** is the field dealing with the topological properties and smooth properties of smooth manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] In this sense differential topology is distinct from the closely related field of differential geometry, which concerns the *geometric* properties of smooth manifolds, including notions of size, distance, and rigid shape.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] By comparison differential topology is concerned with coarser properties, such as the number of holes in a manifold, its homotopy type, or the structure of its diffeomorphism group.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Because many of these coarser properties may be captured algebraically, differential topology has strong links to algebraic topology.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] The central goal of the field of differential topology is the classification of all smooth manifolds up to diffeomorphism.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Beginning in dimension 4, the classification becomes much more difficult for two reasons.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Firstly, every finitely presented group appears as the fundamental group of some 4-manifold, and since the fundamental group is a diffeomorphism invariant, this makes the classification of 4-manifolds at least as difficult as the classification of finitely presented groups.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] By the word problem for groups, which is equivalent to the halting problem, it is impossible to classify such groups, so a full topological classification is impossible.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Secondly, beginning in dimension four it is possible to have smooth manifolds that are homeomorphic, but with distinct, non-diffeomorphic smooth structures.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] This is true even for the Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{4}$ , which admits many exotic $\mathbb {R} ^{4}$ structures.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] This means that the study of differential topology in dimensions 4 and higher must use tools genuinely outside the realm of the regular continuous topology of topological manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] One of the central open problems in differential topology is the four-dimensional smooth Poincaré conjecture, which asks if every smooth 4-manifold that is homeomorphic to the 4-sphere, is also diffeomorphic to it.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] That is, does the 4-sphere admit only one smooth structure?
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] This conjecture is true in dimensions 1, 2, and 3, by the above classification results, but is known to be false in dimension 7 due to the Milnor spheres.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Morse theory is an important tool which studies smooth manifolds by considering the critical points of differentiable functions on the manifold, demonstrating how the smooth structure of the manifold enters into the set of tools available.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Oftentimes more geometric or analytical techniques may be used, by equipping a smooth manifold with a Riemannian metric or by studying a differential equation on it.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Care must be taken to ensure that the resulting information is insensitive to this choice of extra structure, and so genuinely reflects only the topological properties of the underlying smooth manifold.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] For example, the Hodge theorem provides a geometric and analytical interpretation of the de Rham cohomology, and gauge theory was used by Simon Donaldson to prove facts about the intersection form of simply connected 4-manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] In some cases techniques from contemporary physics may appear, such as topological quantum field theory, which can be used to compute topological invariants of smooth spaces.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Famous theorems in differential topology include the Whitney embedding theorem, the hairy ball theorem, the Hopf theorem, the Poincaré–Hopf theorem, Donaldson's theorem, and the Poincaré conjecture.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Differential topology considers the properties and structures that require only a smooth structure on a manifold to be defined.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Smooth manifolds are 'softer' than manifolds with extra geometric structures, which can act as obstructions to certain types of equivalences and deformations that exist in differential topology.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] For instance, volume and Riemannian curvature are invariants that can distinguish different geometric structures on the same smooth manifold—that is, one can smoothly "flatten out" certain manifolds, but it might require distorting the space and affecting the curvature or volume.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] On the other hand, smooth manifolds are more rigid than the topological manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] John Milnor discovered that some spheres have more than one smooth structure—see Exotic sphere and Donaldson's theorem.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Michel Kervaire exhibited topological manifolds with no smooth structure at all.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Some constructions of smooth manifold theory, such as the existence of tangent bundles, can be done in the topological setting with much more work, and others cannot.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] One of the main topics in differential topology is the study of special kinds of smooth mappings between manifolds, namely immersions and submersions, and the intersections of submanifolds via transversality.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] More generally one is interested in properties and invariants of smooth manifolds that are carried over by diffeomorphisms, another special kind of smooth mapping.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Morse theory is another branch of differential topology, in which topological information about a manifold is deduced from changes in the rank of the Jacobian of a function.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] For a list of differential topology topics, see the following reference: List of differential geometry topics.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Differential topology and differential geometry are first characterized by their *similarity*.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] They both study primarily the properties of differentiable manifolds, sometimes with a variety of structures imposed on them.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] One major difference lies in the nature of the problems that each subject tries to address.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] In one view, differential topology distinguishes itself from differential geometry by studying primarily those problems that are *inherently global*.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Consider the example of a coffee cup and a donut.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] From the point of view of differential topology, the donut and the coffee cup are *the same* (in a sense).
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] This is an inherently global view, though, because there is no way for the differential topologist to tell whether the two objects are the same (in this sense) by looking at just a tiny (*local*) piece of either of them.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] They must have access to each entire (*global*) object.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] From the point of view of differential geometry, the coffee cup and the donut are *different* because it is impossible to rotate the coffee cup in such a way that its configuration matches that of the donut.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] This is also a global way of thinking about the problem.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] But an important distinction is that the geometer does not need the entire object to decide this.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] By looking, for instance, at just a tiny piece of the handle, they can decide that the coffee cup is different from the donut because the handle is thinner (or more curved) than any piece of the donut.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] To put it succinctly, differential topology studies structures on manifolds that, in a sense, have no interesting local structure.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Differential geometry studies structures on manifolds that do have an interesting local (or sometimes even infinitesimal) structure.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] More mathematically, for example, the problem of constructing a diffeomorphism between two manifolds of the same dimension is inherently global since *locally* two such manifolds are always diffeomorphic.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Likewise, the problem of computing a quantity on a manifold that is invariant under differentiable mappings is inherently global, since any local invariant will be *trivial* in the sense that it is already exhibited in the topology of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Moreover, differential topology does not restrict itself necessarily to the study of diffeomorphism.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] For example, symplectic topology—a subbranch of differential topology—studies global properties of symplectic manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Differential geometry concerns itself with problems—which may be local *or* global—that always have some non-trivial local properties.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Thus differential geometry may study differentiable manifolds equipped with a *connection*, a *metric* (which may be Riemannian, pseudo-Riemannian, or Finsler), a special sort of *distribution* (such as a CR structure), and so on.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] This distinction between differential geometry and differential topology is blurred, however, in questions specifically pertaining to local diffeomorphism invariants such as the tangent space at a point.
[src:differential-topology/differential-topology] Differential topology also deals with questions like these, which specifically pertain to the properties of differentiable mappings on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ (for example the tangent bundle, jet bundles, the Whitney extension theorem, and so forth).
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] In mathematics, specifically in differential topology, **Morse theory** enables one to analyze the topology of a manifold by studying differentiable functions on that manifold.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] According to the basic insights of Marston Morse, a typical differentiable function on a manifold will reflect the topology quite directly.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Morse theory allows one to find CW structures and handle decompositions on manifolds and to obtain substantial information about their homology.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Before Morse, Arthur Cayley and James Clerk Maxwell had developed some of the ideas of Morse theory in the context of topography.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Morse originally applied his theory to geodesics (critical points of the energy functional on the space of paths).
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] These techniques were used in Raoul Bott's proof of his periodicity theorem.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] The analogue of Morse theory for complex manifolds is Picard–Lefschetz theory.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] To illustrate, consider a mountainous landscape surface M (more generally, a manifold).
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] If f is the function $M\to \mathbb {R}$ giving the elevation of each point, then the inverse image of a point in $\mathbb {R}$ is a contour line (more generally, a level set).
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Each connected component of a contour line is either a point, a simple closed curve, or a closed curve with double point(s).
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Contour lines may also have points of higher order (triple points, etc.), but these are unstable and may be removed by a slight deformation of the landscape.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Double points in contour lines occur at saddle points, or passes, where the surrounding landscape curves up in one direction and down in the other.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Imagine flooding this landscape with water.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] When the water reaches elevation a , the underwater surface is $M^{a}\,{\stackrel {\text{def}}{=}}\,f^{-1}(-\infty ,a]$ , the points with elevation a or below.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Consider how the topology of this surface changes as the water rises.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] It appears unchanged except when a passes the height of a critical point, where the gradient of f is 0 (more generally, the Jacobian matrix acting as a linear map between tangent spaces does not have maximal rank).
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] In other words, the topology of $M^{a}$ does not change except when the water either (1) starts filling a basin, (2) covers a saddle (a mountain pass), or (3) submerges a peak.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] To these three types of critical points—basins, passes, and peaks (i.e. minima, saddles, and maxima)—one associates a number called the index, the number of independent directions in which f decreases from the point.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] More precisely, the index of a non-degenerate critical point p of f is the dimension of the largest subspace of the tangent space to M at p on which the Hessian of f is negative definite.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] The indices of basins, passes, and peaks are $0,1,$ and $2,$ respectively.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Considering a more general surface, let M be a torus oriented as in the picture, with f again taking a point to its height above the plane.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] One can again analyze how the topology of the underwater surface $M^{a}$ changes as the water level a rises.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Starting from the bottom of the torus, let $p,q,r,$ and s be the four critical points of index $0,1,1,$ and 2 corresponding to the basin, two saddles, and peak, respectively.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] When a is less than $f(p)=0,$ then $M^{a}$ is the empty set.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] After a passes the level of $p,$ when $0<a<f(q),$ then $M^{a}$ is a disk, which is homotopy equivalent to a point (a 0-cell) which has been "attached" to the empty set.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Next, when a exceeds the level of $q,$ and $f(q)<a<f(r),$ then $M^{a}$ is a cylinder, and is homotopy equivalent to a disk with a 1-cell attached (image at left).
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Once a passes the level of $r,$ and $f(r)<a<f(s),$ then $M^{a}$ is a torus with a disk removed, which is homotopy equivalent to a cylinder with a 1-cell attached (image at right).
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Finally, when a is greater than the critical level of $s,$ $M^{a}$ is a torus, i.e. a torus with a disk (a 2-cell) removed and re-attached.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] This illustrates the following rule: the topology of $M^{a}$ does not change except when a passes the height of a critical point; at this point, a $\gamma$ -cell is attached to $M^{a}$ , where $\gamma$ is the index of the point.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] This does not address what happens when two critical points are at the same height, which can be resolved by a slight perturbation of $f.$ In the case of a landscape or a manifold embedded in Euclidean space, this perturbation might simply be tilting slightly, rotating the coordinate system.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] One must take care to make the critical points non-degenerate.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] This situation is unstable, since by slightly deforming f to $f(x)=x^{3}+\epsilon x$ , the degenerate critical point is either removed ( $\epsilon >0$ ) or breaks up into two non-degenerate critical points ( $\epsilon <0$ ).
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] For a real-valued smooth function $f:M\to \mathbb {R}$ on a differentiable manifold $M,$ the points where the differential of f vanishes are called critical points of f and their images under f are called critical values.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] If at a critical point p the matrix of second partial derivatives (the Hessian matrix) is non-singular, then p is called a ***non-degenerate critical point***; if the Hessian is singular then p is a ***degenerate critical point***.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] For the functions $f(x)=a+bx+cx^{2}+dx^{3}+\cdots$ from $\mathbb {R}$ to $\mathbb {R} ,$ f has a critical point at the origin if $b=0,$ which is non-degenerate if $c\neq 0$ (that is, f is of the form $a+cx^{2}+\cdots$ ) and degenerate if $c=0$ (that is, f is of the form $a+dx^{3}+\cdots$ ).
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] A less trivial example of a degenerate critical point is the origin of the monkey saddle.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] The **index** of a non-degenerate critical point p of f is the dimension of the largest subspace of the tangent space to M at p on which the Hessian is negative definite.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] This corresponds to the intuitive notion that the index is the number of directions in which f decreases.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] The degeneracy and index of a critical point are independent of the choice of the local coordinate system used, as shown by Sylvester's Law.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] As a corollary of the Morse lemma, one sees that non-degenerate critical points are isolated.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] (Regarding an extension to the complex domain see Complex Morse Lemma.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] For a generalization, see Morse–Palais lemma).
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] A smooth real-valued function on a manifold M is a **Morse function** if it has no degenerate critical points.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] A basic result of Morse theory says that almost all functions are Morse functions.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Technically, the Morse functions form an open, dense subset of all smooth functions $M\to \mathbb {R}$ in the $C^{2}$ topology.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] This is sometimes expressed as "a typical function is Morse" or "a generic function is Morse".
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] As indicated before, we are interested in the question of when the topology of $M^{a}=f^{-1}(-\infty ,a]$ changes as a varies.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Half of the answer to this question is given by the following theorem.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] It is also of interest to know how the topology of $M^{a}$ changes when a passes a critical point.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] The following theorem answers that question.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] These results generalize and formalize the 'rule' stated in the previous section.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Morse theory can be used to prove some strong results on the homology of manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] This gives a powerful tool to study manifold topology.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Suppose on a closed manifold there exists a Morse function $f:M\to \mathbb {R}$ with precisely *k* critical points.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] In what way does the existence of the function f restrict M ?
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] The case $k=2$ was studied by Georges Reeb in 1952; the Reeb sphere theorem states that M is homeomorphic to a sphere $S^{n}.$ The case $k=3$ is possible only in a small number of low dimensions, and *M* is homeomorphic to an Eells–Kuiper manifold.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Morse theory has been used to classify closed 2-manifolds up to diffeomorphism.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] If M is oriented, then M is classified by its genus g and is diffeomorphic to a sphere with g handles: thus if $g=0,$ M is diffeomorphic to the 2-sphere; and if $g>0,$ M is diffeomorphic to the connected sum of g 2-tori.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] If N is unorientable, it is classified by a number $g>0$ and is diffeomorphic to the connected sum of g real projective spaces $\mathbf {RP} ^{2}.$ In particular two closed 2-manifolds are homeomorphic if and only if they are diffeomorphic.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Morse homology is a particularly easy way to understand the homology of smooth manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] It is defined using a generic choice of Morse function and Riemannian metric.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] An infinite dimensional analog of Morse homology in symplectic geometry is known as Floer homology.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] The notion of a Morse function can be generalized to consider functions that have nondegenerate manifolds of critical points.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] A **Morse–Bott function** is a smooth function on a manifold whose critical set is a closed submanifold and whose Hessian is non-degenerate in the normal direction.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] (Equivalently, the kernel of the Hessian at a critical point equals the tangent space to the critical submanifold.) A Morse function is the special case where the critical manifolds are zero-dimensional (so the Hessian at critical points is non-degenerate in every direction, that is, has no kernel).
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] The index is most naturally thought of as a pair $\left(i_{-},i_{+}\right),$ where $i_{-}$ is the dimension of the unstable manifold at a given point of the critical manifold, and $i_{+}$ is equal to $i_{-}$ plus the dimension of the critical manifold.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Morse–Bott functions are useful because generic Morse functions are difficult to work with; the functions one can visualize, and with which one can easily calculate, typically have symmetries.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] They often lead to positive-dimensional critical manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Raoul Bott used Morse–Bott theory in his original proof of the Bott periodicity theorem.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Round functions are examples of Morse–Bott functions, where the critical sets are (disjoint unions of) circles.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Morse homology can also be formulated for Morse–Bott functions; the differential in Morse–Bott homology is computed by a spectral sequence.
[src:differential-topology/morse-theory] Frederic Bourgeois sketched an approach in the course of his work on a Morse–Bott version of symplectic field theory, but this work was never published due to substantial analytic difficulties.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] In mathematics, the **tangent space** of a manifold is a generalization of *tangent lines* to curves in two-dimensional space and *tangent planes* to surfaces in three-dimensional space in higher dimensions.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] In the context of physics, the tangent space to a manifold at a point can be viewed as the space of possible velocities for a particle moving on the manifold.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] In differential geometry, one can attach to every point x of a differentiable manifold a *tangent space*—a real vector space that intuitively contains the possible directions in which one can tangentially pass through x .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] The elements of the tangent space at x are called the *tangent vectors* at x .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] This is a generalization of the notion of a vector, based at a given initial point, in a Euclidean space.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] The dimension of the tangent space at every point of a connected manifold is the same as that of the manifold itself.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] For example, if the given manifold is a 2 -sphere, then one can picture the tangent space at a point as the plane that touches the sphere at that point and is perpendicular to the sphere's radius through the point.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] More generally, if a given manifold is thought of as an embedded submanifold of Euclidean space, then one can picture a tangent space in this literal fashion.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] This was the traditional approach toward defining parallel transport.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Many authors in differential geometry and general relativity use it.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] More strictly, this defines an affine tangent space, which is distinct from the space of tangent vectors described by modern terminology.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] In algebraic geometry, in contrast, there is an intrinsic definition of the *tangent space at a point* of an algebraic variety V that gives a vector space with dimension at least that of V itself.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] The points p at which the dimension of the tangent space is exactly that of V are called *non-singular* points; the others are called *singular* points.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] For example, a curve that crosses itself does not have a unique tangent line at that point.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] The singular points of V are those where the "test to be a manifold" fails.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Once the tangent spaces of a manifold have been introduced, one can define vector fields, which are abstractions of the velocity field of particles moving in space.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] A vector field attaches to every point of the manifold a vector from the tangent space at that point, in a smooth manner.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Such a vector field serves to define a generalized ordinary differential equation on a manifold: A solution to such a differential equation is a differentiable curve on the manifold whose derivative at any point is equal to the tangent vector attached to that point by the vector field.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] All the tangent spaces of a manifold may be "glued together" to form a new differentiable manifold with twice the dimension of the original manifold, called the *tangent bundle* of the manifold.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] The informal description above relies on a manifold's ability to be embedded into an ambient vector space $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ so that the tangent vectors can "stick out" of the manifold into the ambient space.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] However, it is more convenient to define the notion of a tangent space based solely on the manifold itself.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] There are various equivalent ways of defining the tangent spaces of a manifold.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] While the definition via the velocity of curves is intuitively the simplest, it is also the most cumbersome to work with.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] More elegant and abstract approaches are described below.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] In the embedded-manifold picture, a tangent vector at a point x is thought of as the *velocity* of a curve passing through the point x .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] We can therefore define a tangent vector as an equivalence class of curves passing through x while being tangent to each other at x .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Suppose that M is a $C^{k}$ differentiable manifold (with smoothness $k\geq 1$ ) and that $x\in M$ .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Pick a coordinate chart $\varphi :U\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , where U is an open subset of M containing x .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Then $\gamma _{1}$ and $\gamma _{2}$ are said to be *equivalent* at 0 if and only if the derivatives of $\varphi \circ \gamma _{1}$ and $\varphi \circ \gamma _{2}$ at 0 coincide.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] This defines an equivalence relation on the set of all differentiable curves initialized at x , and equivalence classes of such curves are known as *tangent vectors* of M at x .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] The equivalence class of any such curve $\gamma$ is denoted by $\gamma '(0)$ .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] The *tangent space* of M at x , denoted by $T_{x}M$ , is then defined as the set of all tangent vectors at x ; it does not depend on the choice of coordinate chart $\varphi :U\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] The map $\mathrm {d} {\varphi }_{x}$ turns out to be bijective and may be used to transfer the vector-space operations on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ over to $T_{x}M$ , thus turning the latter set into an n -dimensional real vector space.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Again, one needs to check that this construction does not depend on the particular chart $\varphi :U\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and the curve $\gamma$ being used, and in fact it does not.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Suppose now that M is a $C^{\infty }$ manifold.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] A real-valued function $f:M\to \mathbb {R}$ is said to belong to ${C^{\infty }}(M)$ if and only if for every coordinate chart $\varphi :U\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , the map $f\circ \varphi ^{-1}:\varphi [U]\subseteq \mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R}$ is infinitely differentiable.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Note that ${C^{\infty }}(M)$ is a real associative algebra with respect to the pointwise product and sum of functions and scalar multiplication.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] A *derivation* at $x\in M$ is defined as a linear map $D:{C^{\infty }}(M)\to \mathbb {R}$ that satisfies the Leibniz identity $\forall f,g\in {C^{\infty }}(M):\qquad D(fg)=D(f)\cdot g(x)+f(x)\cdot D(g),$ which is modeled on the product rule of calculus.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] (For every identically constant function $f={\text{const}},$ it follows that $D(f)=0$ ).
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Generalizations of this definition are possible, for instance, to complex manifolds and algebraic varieties.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] However, instead of examining derivations D from the full algebra of functions, one must instead work at the level of germs of functions.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] The reason for this is that the structure sheaf may not be fine for such structures.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] For example, let X be an algebraic variety with structure sheaf ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Then the Zariski tangent space at a point $p\in X$ is the collection of all $\mathbb {k}$ -derivations $D:{\mathcal {O}}_{X,p}\to \mathbb {k}$ , where $\mathbb {k}$ is the ground field and ${\mathcal {O}}_{X,p}$ is the stalk of ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ at p .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] For $x\in M$ and a differentiable curve ${\displaystyle \gamma$ such that $\gamma (0)=x,$ define ${D_{\gamma }}(f):=(f\circ \gamma )'(0)$ (where the derivative is taken in the ordinary sense because $f\circ \gamma$ is a function from $(-1,1)$ to $\mathbb {R}$ ).
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] One can ascertain that $D_{\gamma }(f)$ is a derivation at the point $x,$ and that equivalent curves yield the same derivation.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Thus, for an equivalence class $\gamma '(0),$ we can define ${D_{\gamma '(0)}}(f):=(f\circ \gamma )'(0),$ where the curve $\gamma \in \gamma '(0)$ has been chosen arbitrarily.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Again, we start with a $C^{\infty }$ manifold M and a point $x\in M$ .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Consider the ideal I of $C^{\infty }(M)$ that consists of all smooth functions f vanishing at x , i.e., $f(x)=0$ .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Then I and $I^{2}$ are both real vector spaces, and the quotient space $I/I^{2}$ can be shown to be isomorphic to the cotangent space $T_{x}^{*}M$ through the use of Taylor's theorem.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] The tangent space $T_{x}M$ may then be defined as the dual space of $I/I^{2}$ .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] While this definition is the most abstract, it is also the one that is most easily transferable to other settings, for instance, to the varieties considered in algebraic geometry.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] If D is a derivation at x , then $D(f)=0$ for every $f\in I^{2}$ , which means that D gives rise to a linear map $I/I^{2}\to \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Conversely, if $r:I/I^{2}\to \mathbb {R}$ is a linear map, then $D(f):=r\left((f-f(x))+I^{2}\right)$ defines a derivation at x .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] This yields an equivalence between tangent spaces defined via derivations and tangent spaces defined via cotangent spaces.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] If M is an open subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , then M is a $C^{\infty }$ manifold in a natural manner (take coordinate charts to be identity maps on open subsets of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ), and the tangent spaces are all naturally identified with $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Another way to think about tangent vectors is as directional derivatives.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] This map is naturally a derivation at x .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Furthermore, every derivation at a point in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is of this form.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Hence, there is a one-to-one correspondence between vectors (thought of as tangent vectors at a point) and derivations at a point.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] As tangent vectors to a general manifold at a point can be defined as derivations at that point, it is natural to think of them as directional derivatives.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] This formula therefore expresses v as a linear combination of the basis tangent vectors ${\textstyle \left.{\frac {\partial }{\partial x^{i}}}\right|_{p}\in T_{p}M}$ defined by the coordinate chart $\varphi :U\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] The linear map $\mathrm {d} {\varphi }_{x}$ is called variously the *derivative*, *total derivative*, *differential*, or *pushforward* of $\varphi$ at x .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] In a sense, the derivative is the best linear approximation to $\varphi$ near x .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] Note that when $N=\mathbb {R}$ , then the map $\mathrm {d} {\varphi }_{x}:T_{x}M\to \mathbb {R}$ coincides with the usual notion of the differential of the function $\varphi$ .
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] In local coordinates the derivative of $\varphi$ is given by the Jacobian.
[src:differential-topology/tangent-space] This is a generalization of the inverse function theorem to maps between manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] In mathematics, **transversality** is a notion that describes how spaces can intersect; transversality can be seen as the "opposite" of *tangency*, and plays a role in general position.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] It formalizes the idea of a generic intersection in differential topology.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] It is defined by considering the linearizations of the intersecting spaces at the points of intersection.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] Two submanifolds of a given finite-dimensional smooth manifold are said to **intersect transversally** if at every point of intersection, their separate tangent spaces at that point together generate the tangent space of the ambient manifold at that point.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] Manifolds that do not intersect are vacuously transverse.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] If the manifolds are of complementary dimension (i.e., their dimensions add up to the dimension of the ambient space), the condition means that the tangent space to the ambient manifold is the direct sum of the two smaller tangent spaces.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] If an intersection is transverse, then the intersection will be a submanifold whose codimension is equal to the sums of the codimensions of the two manifolds.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] In the absence of the transversality condition the intersection may fail to be a submanifold, having some sort of singular point.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] In particular, this means that transverse submanifolds of complementary dimension intersect in isolated points (i.e., a 0-manifold).
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] If both submanifolds and the ambient manifold are oriented, their intersection is oriented.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] When the intersection is zero-dimensional, the orientation is simply a plus or minus for each point.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] One notation for the transverse intersection of two submanifolds $L_{1}$ and $L_{2}$ of a given manifold M is $L_{1}\pitchfork L_{2}$ .
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] This notation can be read in two ways: either as “ $L_{1}$ and $L_{2}$ intersect transversally” or as an alternative notation for the set-theoretic intersection $L_{1}\cap L_{2}$ of $L_{1}$ and $L_{2}$ when that intersection is transverse.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] If the maps are embeddings, this is equivalent to transversality of submanifolds.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] The meaning of transversality differs a lot depending on the relative dimensions of $M,L_{1}$ and $L_{2}$ .
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] The relationship between transversality and tangency is clearest when $\ell _{1}+\ell _{2}=m$ .
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] When $\ell _{1}+\ell _{2}=m$ , the image of $L_{1}$ and $L_{2}$ 's tangent spaces must sum directly to M 's tangent space at any point of intersection.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] Their intersection thus consists of isolated points, i.e. it is a zero-dimensional manifold.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] If $L_{1}$ and $L_{2}$ are oriented, then one can assign a sign to each such point.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] In fact it *cannot* be direct if $f_{1}$ and $f_{2}$ are immersions at their point of intersection, as happens in the case of embedded submanifolds.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] Given any two smooth submanifolds, it is possible to perturb either of them by an arbitrarily small amount such that the resulting submanifold intersects transversally with the fixed submanifold.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] Such perturbations do not affect the homology class of the manifolds or of their intersections.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] For example, if manifolds of complementary dimension intersect transversally, the signed sum of the number of their intersection points does not change even if we isotope the manifolds to another transverse intersection.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] (The intersection points can be counted modulo 2, ignoring the signs, to obtain a coarser invariant.) This descends to a bilinear intersection product on homology classes of any dimension, which is Poincaré dual to the cup product on cohomology.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] Like the cup product, the intersection product is graded-commutative.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] The simplest non-trivial example of transversality is of arcs in a surface.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] An intersection point between two arcs is transverse if and only if it is not a tangency, i.e., their tangent lines inside the tangent plane to the surface are distinct.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] In a three-dimensional space, two curves can be transverse only when they have empty intersection, since their tangent spaces could generate at most a two-dimensional space.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] Curves transverse to surfaces intersect in points, and surfaces transverse to each other intersect in curves.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] Curves that are tangent to a surface at a point (for instance, curves lying on a surface) do not intersect the surface transversally.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] Here is a more specialised example: suppose that G is a simple Lie group and ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is its Lie algebra.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] By the Jacobson–Morozov theorem every nilpotent element $e\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ can be included into an ${\mathfrak {sl_{2}}}$ -triple $(e,h,f)$ .
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] The space $[{\mathfrak {g}},e]$ is the tangent space at e to the adjoint orbit ${\rm {{Ad}(G)e}}$ and so the affine space $e+{\mathfrak {g}}_{f}$ intersects the orbit of e transversally.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] The space $e+{\mathfrak {g}}_{f}$ is known as the "Slodowy slice" after Peter Slodowy.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] In fields utilizing the calculus of variations or the related Pontryagin maximum principle, the transversality condition is frequently used to control the types of solutions found in optimization problems.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] where one or both of the endpoints of the curve are not fixed.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] In many of these problems, the solution satisfies the condition that the solution curve should cross transversally the nullcline or some other curve describing terminal conditions.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] Using Sard's theorem, whose hypothesis is a special case of the transversality of maps, it can be shown that transverse intersections between submanifolds of a space of complementary dimensions or between submanifolds and maps to a space are themselves smooth submanifolds.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] The signs agree with the indices of the vector field, and thus the sum of the signs—i.e. the fundamental class of the zero set—is equal to the Euler characteristic of the manifold.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] For an infinite-dimensional example, the d-bar operator is a section of a certain Banach space bundle over the space of maps from a Riemann surface into an almost-complex manifold.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] The zero set of this section consists of holomorphic maps.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] If the d-bar operator can be shown to be transverse to the zero-section, this moduli space will be a smooth manifold.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] These considerations play a fundamental role in the theory of pseudoholomorphic curves and Gromov–Witten theory.
[src:differential-topology/transversality-mathematics] For this example, the definition of transversality has to be refined in order to deal with Banach spaces.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] In vector calculus and physics, a **vector field** is an assignment of a vector to each point in a space, most commonly Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] A vector field on a plane can be visualized as a collection of arrows with given magnitudes and directions, each attached to a point on the plane.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Vector fields often have unit of measurement (for example, metres or kilometres per hour), forming a vector physical quantity.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] They may be used to model, for example, the speed and direction of a moving fluid throughout three dimensional space, such as the wind, or the strength and direction of some force, such as the magnetic or gravitational force, as it changes from one point to another point.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The elements of differential and integral calculus extend naturally to vector fields.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] When a vector field represents force, the line integral of a vector field represents the work done by a force moving along a path, and under this interpretation conservation of energy is exhibited as a special case of the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Vector fields can usefully be thought of as representing the velocity of a moving flow in space, and this physical intuition leads to notions such as the divergence (which represents the rate of change of volume of a flow) and curl (which represents the rotation of a flow).
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] A vector field is a special case of a *vector-valued function*, whose domain's dimension has no relation to the dimension of its range; for example, the position vector of a space curve is defined only for smaller subset of the ambient space.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Likewise, n coordinates, a vector field on a domain in *n*-dimensional Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ can be represented as a vector-valued function that associates an *n*-tuple of real numbers to each point of the domain.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] This representation of a vector field depends on the coordinate system, and there is a well-defined transformation law (*covariance and contravariance of vectors*) in passing from one coordinate system to the other.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Vector fields are often discussed on open subsets of Euclidean space, but also make sense on other subsets such as surfaces, where they associate an arrow tangent to the surface at each point (a tangent vector).
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] More generally, vector fields are defined on differentiable manifolds, which are spaces that look like Euclidean space on small scales, but may have more complicated structure on larger scales.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] In this setting, a vector field gives a tangent vector at each point of the manifold (that is, a section of the tangent bundle to the manifold).
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Vector fields are one kind of tensor field.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The arrows depict the field at discrete points, however, the field exists everywhere.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Given a subset *S* of **R***n*, a **vector field** is represented by a vector-valued function *V*: *S* → **R***n* in standard Cartesian coordinates (*x*1, …, *x**n*).
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] If each component of *V* is continuous, then *V* is a continuous vector field.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] It is common to focus on **smooth** vector fields, meaning that each component is a smooth function (differentiable any number of times).
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] A vector field can be visualized as assigning a vector to individual points within an *n*-dimensional space.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] One standard notation is to write ${\frac {\partial }{\partial x_{1}}},\ldots ,{\frac {\partial }{\partial x_{n}}}$ for the unit vectors in the coordinate directions.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] In these terms, every smooth vector field V on an open subset S of ${\mathbf {R} }^{n}$ can be written as $\sum _{i=1}^{n}V_{i}(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}){\frac {\partial }{\partial x_{i}}}$ for some smooth functions $V_{1},\ldots ,V_{n}$ on S .
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The reason for this notation is that a vector field determines a linear map from the space of smooth functions to itself, $V\colon C^{\infty }(S)\to C^{\infty }(S)$ , given by differentiating in the direction of the vector field.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] In physics, a vector is additionally distinguished by how its coordinates change when one measures the same vector with respect to a different background coordinate system.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The transformation properties of vectors distinguish a vector as a geometrically distinct entity from a simple list of scalars, or from a covector.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Thus, suppose that (*x*1, ..., *x**n*) is a choice of Cartesian coordinates, in terms of which the components of the vector V are $V_{x}=(V_{1,x},\dots ,V_{n,x})$ and suppose that (*y*1,...,*y**n*) are *n* functions of the *x**i* defining a different coordinate system.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Such a transformation law is called contravariant.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] A similar transformation law characterizes vector fields in physics: specifically, a vector field is a specification of *n* functions in each coordinate system subject to the transformation law (**1**) relating the different coordinate systems.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Vector fields are thus contrasted with scalar fields, which associate a number or *scalar* to every point in space, and are also contrasted with simple lists of scalar fields, which do not transform under coordinate changes.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Given a differentiable manifold M , a **vector field** on M is an assignment of a tangent vector to each point in M .
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] More precisely, a vector field F is a mapping from M into the tangent bundle $TM$ so that $p\circ F$ is the identity mapping where p denotes the projection from $TM$ to M .
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] In other words, a vector field is a section of the tangent bundle.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] An alternative definition: A smooth vector field X on a manifold M is a linear map $X:C^{\infty }(M)\to C^{\infty }(M)$ such that X is a derivation: $X(fg)=fX(g)+X(f)g$ for all $f,g\in C^{\infty }(M)$ .
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] If the manifold M is smooth or analytic—that is, the change of coordinates is smooth (analytic)—then one can make sense of the notion of smooth (analytic) vector fields.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The collection of all smooth vector fields on a smooth manifold M is often denoted by $\Gamma (TM)$ or $C^{\infty }(M,TM)$ (especially when thinking of vector fields as sections); the collection of all smooth vector fields is also denoted by ${\textstyle {\mathfrak {X}}(M)}$ (a fraktur "X").
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Vector fields can be constructed out of scalar fields using the gradient operator (denoted by the del: ∇).
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The associated flow is called the **gradient flow**, and is used in the method of gradient descent.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] We say central fields are invariant under orthogonal transformations around 0.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The point 0 is called the **center** of the field.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Since orthogonal transformations are actually rotations and reflections, the invariance conditions mean that vectors of a central field are always directed towards, or away from, 0; this is an alternate (and simpler) definition.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] A central field is always a gradient field, since defining it on one semiaxis and integrating gives an antigradient.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] A common technique in physics is to integrate a vector field along a curve, also called determining its line integral.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Intuitively this is summing up all vector components in line with the tangents to the curve, expressed as their scalar products.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] For example, given a particle in a force field (e.g. gravitation), where each vector at some point in space represents the force acting there on the particle, the line integral along a certain path is the work done on the particle, when it travels along this path.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Intuitively, it is the sum of the scalar products of the force vector and the small tangent vector in each point along the curve.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The line integral is constructed analogously to the Riemann integral and it exists if the curve is rectifiable (has finite length) and the vector field is continuous.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] To show vector field topology one can use line integral convolution.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The divergence of a vector field on Euclidean space is a function (or scalar field).
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] with the obvious generalization to arbitrary dimensions.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The divergence at a point represents the degree to which a small volume around the point is a source or a sink for the vector flow, a result which is made precise by the divergence theorem.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The divergence can also be defined on a Riemannian manifold, that is, a manifold with a Riemannian metric that measures the length of vectors.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The curl is an operation which takes a vector field and produces another vector field.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The curl is defined only in three dimensions, but some properties of the curl can be captured in higher dimensions with the exterior derivative.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The curl measures the density of the angular momentum of the vector flow at a point, that is, the amount to which the flow circulates around a fixed axis.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] This intuitive description is made precise by Stokes' theorem.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The index of a vector field is an integer that helps describe its behaviour around an isolated zero (i.e., an isolated singularity of the field).
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] In the plane, the index takes the value −1 at a saddle singularity but +1 at a source or sink singularity.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Let *n be* the dimension of the manifold on which the vector field is defined.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Take a closed surface (homeomorphic to the (n-1)-sphere) S around the zero, so that no other zeros lie in the interior of S.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] A map from this sphere to a unit sphere of dimension *n* − 1 can be constructed by dividing each vector on this sphere by its length to form a unit length vector, which is a point on the unit sphere S*n*−1.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] This defines a continuous map from S to S*n*−1.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The index of the vector field at the point is the degree of this map.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] It can be shown that this integer does not depend on the choice of S, and therefore depends only on the vector field itself.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The index is not defined at any non-singular point (i.e., a point where the vector is non-zero).
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] It is equal to +1 around a source, and more generally equal to (−1)*k* around a saddle that has *k* contracting dimensions and *n*−*k* expanding dimensions.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] For an ordinary (2-dimensional) sphere in three-dimensional space, it can be shown that the index of any vector field on the sphere must be 2.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] This shows that every such vector field must have a zero.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] For a vector field on a compact manifold with finitely many zeroes, the Poincaré-Hopf theorem states that the vector field's index is the manifold's Euler characteristic.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Michael Faraday, in his concept of *lines of force,* emphasized that the field *itself* should be an object of study, which it has become throughout physics in the form of field theory.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] In addition to the magnetic field, other phenomena that were modeled by Faraday include the electrical field and light field.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Consider the flow of a fluid through a region of space.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] At any given time, any point of the fluid has a particular velocity associated with it; thus there is a vector field associated to any flow.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The converse is also true: it is possible to associate a flow to a vector field having that vector field as its velocity.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The curves $\gamma _{x}$ are called **integral curves** or **trajectories** (or less commonly, flow lines) of the vector field V and partition S into equivalence classes.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] It is not always possible to extend the interval $(-\varepsilon ,+\varepsilon )$ to the whole real number line.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The flow may for example reach the edge of S in a finite time.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] In two or three dimensions one can visualize the vector field as giving rise to a flow on S .
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] If we drop a particle into this flow at a point p it will move along the curve $\gamma _{p}$ in the flow depending on the initial point p .
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] If p is a stationary point of V (i.e., the vector field is equal to the zero vector at the point p ), then the particle will remain at p .
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Typical applications are pathline in fluid, geodesic flow, and one-parameter subgroups and the exponential map in Lie groups.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] By definition, a vector field on M is called **complete** if each of its flow curves exists for all time.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] In particular, compactly supported vector fields on a manifold are complete.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] If X is a complete vector field on M , then the one-parameter group of diffeomorphisms generated by the flow along X exists for all time; it is described by a smooth mapping $\mathbf {R} \times M\to M.$ On a compact manifold without boundary, every smooth vector field is complete.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] An example of an **incomplete** vector field V on the real line $\mathbb {R}$ is given by $V(x)=x^{2}$ .
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Hence for $x_{0}\neq 0$ , $x(t)$ is undefined at ${\textstyle t={\frac {1}{x_{0}}}}$ so cannot be defined for all values of t .
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] The flows associated to two vector fields need not commute with each other.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Their failure to commute is described by the Lie bracket of two vector fields, which is again a vector field.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Given a smooth function between manifolds, $f:M\to N$ , the derivative is an induced map on tangent bundles, $f_{*}:TM\to TN$ .
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Given vector fields $V:M\to TM$ and $W:N\to TN$ , we say that W is f -related to V if the equation $W\circ f=f_{*}\circ V$ holds.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Replacing vectors by *p*-vectors (*p*th exterior power of vectors) yields *p*-vector fields; taking the dual space and exterior powers yields differential *k*-forms, and combining these yields general tensor fields.
[src:differential-topology/vector-field] Algebraically, vector fields can be characterized as derivations of the algebra of smooth functions on the manifold, which leads to defining a vector field on a commutative algebra as a derivation on the algebra, which is developed in the theory of differential calculus over commutative algebras.
